 editing the works of other composers, and his innovative piano technique. One chapter is devoted to the Sonata in B Minor, perhaps Liszt's single most celebrated composition.Walker draws heavily on Liszt's astonishingly large personal correspondence with other composers, critics, pianists, and prominent public figures. All the essays reveal Walker's broad and deep knowledge of Liszt and Romantic music generally and, in some cases, his impatience with contemporary performance practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMusicy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aArt History. 4aMusical Arts & Ethnomusicology. 7aMUSIC / Individual Composer & Musician.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171703140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717031423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501717031.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK